Digest 48-9, parricida uiryis sanquineis uerberatus, deinde culleo insuam-r cum cane, yallo gallinaceo et uipera et simia. deinde rin mare profundum culleus iactetur. If there is no sea near, then, according to Hadrian's ordinance, he is to be thrown to wild beasts. Note that par- ricidium includes the murder of any near relation. Nero is the arch—parricide in Roman literature. He deserved not once, but many times to die the parricide's death, as Juvenal says (viii 213, 4):

cuins supplicio non debuit una parari simia nec serpens unus nee culleus unus.
